Below is an example HTML file that includes both a buggy and a corrected version of a progress bar tracker. The buggy version demonstrates a shared state concurrency bug where multiple simulated concurrent tasks update a shared progress percentage variable, causing the bar to show incorrect values or exceed 100%. The corrected version fixes this issue.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Progress Bar Tracker</title>
    <style>
        .progress-bar {
            width: 0%;
            height: 20px;
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            text-align: center;
            color: #fff;
        }
        .progress-bar-container {
            width: 100%;
            height: 20px;
            background-color: #ddd;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            margin-bottom: 10px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<h2>Buggy Version</h2>
<div id="buggy-progress-bar-container" class="progress-bar-container">
    <div id="buggy-progress-bar" class="progress-bar">0%</div>
</div>
<p id="buggy-progress-text">Progress: 0%</p>

<h2>Corrected Version</h2>
<div id="corrected-progress-bar-container" class="progress-bar-container">
    <div id="corrected-progress-bar" class="progress-bar">0%</div>
</div>
<p id="corrected-progress-text">Progress: 0%</p>

<script>
    // Buggy Version
    let buggyProgress = 0;
    const buggyProgressBar = document.getElementById('buggy-progress-bar');
    const buggyProgressBarContainer = document.getElementById('buggy-progress-bar-container');
    const buggyProgressText = document.getElementById('buggy-progress-text');

    function updateBuggyProgress(percentage) {
        buggyProgress += percentage;
        buggyProgressBar.style.width = `${buggyProgress}%`;
        buggyProgressBar.innerText = `${buggyProgress}%`;
        buggyProgressText.innerText = `Progress: ${buggyProgress}%`;
    }

    // Simulate concurrent tasks
    function simulateBuggyTasks() {
        for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
            setTimeout(() => {
                updateBuggyProgress(10);
            }, Math.random() * 1000);
        }
    }
    simulateBuggyTasks();

    // Corrected Version
    let correctedProgress = 0;
    let tasksCompleted = 0;
    const correctedProgressBar = document.getElementById('corrected-progress-bar');
    const correctedProgressBarContainer = document.getElementById('corrected-progress-bar-container');
    const correctedProgressText = document.getElementById('corrected-progress-text');

    function updateCorrectedProgress() {
        tasksCompleted++;
        correctedProgress = Math.min((tasksCompleted / 10) * 100, 100);
        correctedProgressBar.style.width = `${correctedProgress}%`;
        correctedProgressBar.innerText = `${correctedProgress}%`;
        correctedProgressText.innerText = `Progress: ${correctedProgress}%`;
    }

    // Simulate concurrent tasks
    function simulateCorrectedTasks() {
        for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
            new Promise(resolve => {
                setTimeout(() => {
                    resolve();
                }, Math.random() * 1000);
            }).then(() => {
                updateCorrectedProgress();
            });
        }
    }
    simulateCorrectedTasks();
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

**Explanation of the Problem and Fix:**

### Buggy Version

*   The `buggyProgress` variable is shared among all concurrent tasks.
*   Each task increments the `buggyProgress` variable by a certain percentage (10% in this case) without considering the current progress.
*   This leads to a concurrency bug where the progress bar may exceed 100% or show incorrect values.

### Corrected Version

*   Instead of directly updating a shared progress variable, the corrected version uses a `tasksCompleted` counter to track the number of completed tasks.
*   The progress is calculated based on the ratio of completed tasks to the total number of tasks, ensuring that it never exceeds 100%.
*   This approach avoids the concurrency bug by decoupling the progress calculation from the shared state updates.

By comparing the buggy and corrected versions side by side, you can observe the issue and the fix in action. The corrected version ensures that the progress bar accurately reflects the completion status of the simulated tasks.

